\PYGZhy{}\PYGZhy{}\PYGZhy{}

\PYG{g+gu}{\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{} 5 — Exploration Depth}

For each route, \PYG{g+gs}{**deeply explore the page component tree**}:

\PYG{k}{1.} Read the top\PYGZhy{}level page component imported in \PYG{l+s+sb}{`RouteConfig.tsx`}.
\PYG{k}{2.} Follow its child components — read each imported component.
\PYG{k}{3.} Identify all interactive elements: buttons, forms, modals, dropdowns, links, tabs, toggles.
\PYG{k}{4.} Identify data dependencies: what GraphQL queries/mutations are used, what data must exist.
\PYG{k}{5.} Identify conditional UI: what changes based on state, permissions, or data presence.

Use this understanding to write \PYG{g+gs}{**specific, meaningful**} user stories and acceptance criteria — not generic ones.

\PYG{g+gu}{\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{} What makes a good user story}

\PYG{g+gs}{**Good:**} \PYGZdq{}As an HR admin, I want to see a ranked list of people matching a job\PYGZsq{}s required skills, so that I can identify the best internal candidates.\PYGZdq{}

\PYG{g+gs}{**Bad:**} \PYGZdq{}As a user, I want to view the people page, so that I can see people.\PYGZdq{}

\PYG{g+gu}{\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{} What makes good acceptance criteria}

\PYG{g+gs}{**Good:**} \PYGZdq{}Given a job with 3 matching people, when the HR admin navigates to the people tab, then all 3 matches are displayed with their match percentage.\PYGZdq{}

\PYG{g+gs}{**Bad:**} \PYGZdq{}Given a user, when they visit the page, then it loads.\PYGZdq{}

\PYGZhy{}\PYGZhy{}\PYGZhy{}

\PYG{g+gu}{\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{} 6 — Skip Logic}

Before generating a file, check if it already exists in \PYG{l+s+sb}{`playwright/user\PYGZhy{}stories/`}:

\PYG{k}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{+w}{ }If the file exists → \PYG{g+gs}{**skip it entirely**}. Do not overwrite, do not merge.
\PYG{k}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{+w}{ }If the file does not exist → generate it.

\PYGZhy{}\PYGZhy{}\PYGZhy{}

\PYG{g+gu}{\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{} 7 — Scoping}

By default, the skill processes \PYG{g+gs}{**all routes**} from \PYG{l+s+sb}{`RouteConfig.tsx`}.

If the user provides context narrowing the scope:

\PYG{k}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{+w}{ }A specific role (e.g. \PYGZdq{}generate for admin routes\PYGZdq{}) → only process routes in that role group.
\PYG{k}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{+w}{ }A specific route (e.g. \PYGZdq{}generate for /hr/jobs/:id\PYGZdq{}) → only generate that file (and its children if it\PYGZsq{}s a parent).

\PYGZhy{}\PYGZhy{}\PYGZhy{}

\PYG{g+gu}{\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{} 8 — Process}

\PYG{k}{1.} \PYG{g+gs}{**Read `RouteConfig.tsx`**} — extract all routes, their page components, and role groupings.
\PYG{k}{2.} \PYG{g+gs}{**Build the route map**} — determine which routes are parents, children, wizards, or standalone.
\PYG{k}{3.} \PYG{g+gs}{**Check existing files**} — scan \PYG{l+s+sb}{`playwright/user\PYGZhy{}stories/`} for already\PYGZhy{}generated files.
\PYG{k}{4.} \PYG{g+gs}{**For each route group that needs generation:**}
   a. Read the page component(s) deeply — follow the component tree.
   b. Identify user\PYGZhy{}visible features, interactions, data dependencies, and conditional UI.
   c. Reference \PYG{l+s+sb}{`SKILL.md`} lightly for auth fixture names and seed data conventions.
   d. Write the user story file using the appropriate template (standard / parent / child / wizard).
   e. Save to \PYG{l+s+sb}{`playwright/user\PYGZhy{}stories/\PYGZlt{}role\PYGZgt{}/\PYGZlt{}filename\PYGZgt{}.md`}.
\PYG{k}{5.} \PYG{g+gs}{**Print the generation summary.**}

\PYGZhy{}\PYGZhy{}\PYGZhy{}

\PYG{g+gu}{\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{} 9 — Generation Summary}

After processing all routes, output a summary:

\PYG{l+s+sb}{```markdown}
\PYG{g+gu}{\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{} Generation Summary}

\PYG{g+gu}{\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{} Generated (X files)}
\PYG{k}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{+w}{ }✅ public/signin.md
\PYG{k}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{+w}{ }✅ admin/jobs\PYGZhy{}detail.md (parent)
\PYG{k}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{+w}{ }✅ admin/jobs\PYGZhy{}detail\PYGZhy{}people.md (child of jobs\PYGZhy{}detail)
\PYG{k}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{+w}{ }...

\PYG{g+gu}{\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{} Skipped (Y files already exist)}
\PYG{k}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{+w}{ }⏭️ employee/me.md
\PYG{k}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{+w}{ }...

\PYG{g+gu}{\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{} Route Map}
Total routes: N | Grouped into: M files | Generated: X | Skipped: Y
\PYG{l+s+sb}{```}
\end{MintedVerbatim}
